3891     @staticmethod
3892     def _get_blocks_and_items(
3893         block_obj, table_exists, new_non_index_axes, values_axes, data_columns
3894     ):
3895         # Helper to clarify non-state-altering parts of _create_axes
3896 
3897         def get_blk_items(mgr, blocks):
3898             return [mgr.items.take(blk.mgr_locs) for blk in blocks]
3899 
3900         blocks = block_obj._mgr.blocks
3901         blk_items = get_blk_items(block_obj._mgr, blocks)
3902 
3903         if len(data_columns):
3904             axis, axis_labels = new_non_index_axes[0]
3905             new_labels = Index(axis_labels).difference(Index(data_columns))
3906             mgr = block_obj.reindex(new_labels, axis=axis)._mgr
3907 
3908             blocks = list(mgr.blocks)
3909             blk_items = get_blk_items(mgr, blocks)
3910             for c in data_columns:
3911                 mgr = block_obj.reindex([c], axis=axis)._mgr
3912                 blocks.extend(mgr.blocks)
3913                 blk_items.extend(get_blk_items(mgr, mgr.blocks))
3914 
3915         # reorder the blocks in the same order as the existing table if we can
3916         if table_exists:
3917             by_items = {
3918                 tuple(b_items.tolist()): (b, b_items)
3919                 for b, b_items in zip(blocks, blk_items)
3920             }
3921             new_blocks = []
3922             new_blk_items = []
3923             for ea in values_axes:
3924                 items = tuple(ea.values)
3925                 try:
3926                     b, b_items = by_items.pop(items)
3927                     new_blocks.append(b)
3928                     new_blk_items.append(b_items)
3929                 except (IndexError, KeyError) as err:
3930                     jitems = ",".join(pprint_thing(item) for item in items)
3931                     raise ValueError(
3932                         f"cannot match existing table structure for [{jitems}] "
3933                         "on appending data"
3934                     ) from err
3935             blocks = new_blocks
3936             blk_items = new_blk_items
3937 
3938         return blocks, blk_items

3940     def process_axes(self, obj, selection: "Selection", columns=None):
3941         """ process axes filters """
3942         # make a copy to avoid side effects
3943         if columns is not None:
3944             columns = list(columns)
3945 
3946         # make sure to include levels if we have them
3947         if columns is not None and self.is_multi_index:
3948             assert isinstance(self.levels, list)  # assured by is_multi_index
3949             for n in self.levels:
3950                 if n not in columns:
3951                     columns.insert(0, n)
3952 
3953         # reorder by any non_index_axes & limit to the select columns
3954         for axis, labels in self.non_index_axes:
3955             obj = _reindex_axis(obj, axis, labels, columns)
3956 
3957         # apply the selection filters (but keep in the same order)
3958         if selection.filter is not None:
3959             for field, op, filt in selection.filter.format():
3960 
3961                 def process_filter(field, filt):
3962 
3963                     for axis_name in obj._AXIS_ORDERS:
3964                         axis_number = obj._get_axis_number(axis_name)
3965                         axis_values = obj._get_axis(axis_name)
3966                         assert axis_number is not None
3967 
3968                         # see if the field is the name of an axis
3969                         if field == axis_name:
3970 
3971                             # if we have a multi-index, then need to include
3972                             # the levels
3973                             if self.is_multi_index:
3974                                 filt = filt.union(Index(self.levels))
3975 
3976                             takers = op(axis_values, filt)
3977                             return obj.loc(axis=axis_number)[takers]
3978 
3979                         # this might be the name of a file IN an axis
3980                         elif field in axis_values:
3981 
3982                             # we need to filter on this dimension
3983                             values = ensure_index(getattr(obj, field).values)
3984                             filt = ensure_index(filt)
3985 
3986                             # hack until we support reversed dim flags
3987                             if isinstance(obj, DataFrame):
3988                                 axis_number = 1 - axis_number
3989                             takers = op(values, filt)
3990                             return obj.loc(axis=axis_number)[takers]
3991 
3992                     raise ValueError(f"cannot find the field [{field}] for filtering!")
3993 
3994                 obj = process_filter(field, filt)
3995 
3996         return obj

3998     def create_description(
3999         self,
4000         complib,
4001         complevel: Optional[int],
4002         fletcher32: bool,
4003         expectedrows: Optional[int],
4004     ) -> Dict[str, Any]:
4005         """ create the description of the table from the axes & values """
4006         # provided expected rows if its passed
4007         if expectedrows is None:
4008             expectedrows = max(self.nrows_expected, 10000)
4009 
4010         d = dict(name="table", expectedrows=expectedrows)
4011 
4012         # description from the axes & values
4013         d["description"] = {a.cname: a.typ for a in self.axes}
4014 
4015         if complib:
4016             if complevel is None:
4017                 complevel = self._complevel or 9
4018             filters = _tables().Filters(
4019                 complevel=complevel,
4020                 complib=complib,
4021                 fletcher32=fletcher32 or self._fletcher32,
4022             )
4023             d["filters"] = filters
4024         elif self._filters is not None:
4025             d["filters"] = self._filters
4026 
4027         return d

4029     def read_coordinates(
4030         self, where=None, start: Optional[int] = None, stop: Optional[int] = None,
4031     ):
4032         """
4033         select coordinates (row numbers) from a table; return the
4034         coordinates object
4035         """
4036         # validate the version
4037         self.validate_version(where)
4038 
4039         # infer the data kind
4040         if not self.infer_axes():
4041             return False
4042 
4043         # create the selection
4044         selection = Selection(self, where=where, start=start, stop=stop)
4045         coords = selection.select_coords()
4046         if selection.filter is not None:
4047             for field, op, filt in selection.filter.format():
4048                 data = self.read_column(
4049                     field, start=coords.min(), stop=coords.max() + 1
4050                 )
4051                 coords = coords[op(data.iloc[coords - coords.min()], filt).values]
4052 
4053         return Index(coords)
4054 
4055     def read_column(
4056         self,
4057         column: str,
4058         where=None,
4059         start: Optional[int] = None,
4060         stop: Optional[int] = None,
4061     ):
4062         """
4063         return a single column from the table, generally only indexables
4064         are interesting
4065         """
4066         # validate the version
4067         self.validate_version()
4068 
4069         # infer the data kind
4070         if not self.infer_axes():
4071             return False
4072 
4073         if where is not None:
4074             raise TypeError("read_column does not currently accept a where clause")
4075 
4076         # find the axes
4077         for a in self.axes:
4078             if column == a.name:
4079 
4080                 if not a.is_data_indexable:
4081                     raise ValueError(
4082                         f"column [{column}] can not be extracted individually; "
4083                         "it is not data indexable"
4084                     )
4085 
4086                 # column must be an indexable or a data column
4087                 c = getattr(self.table.cols, column)
4088                 a.set_info(self.info)
4089                 col_values = a.convert(
4090                     c[start:stop],
4091                     nan_rep=self.nan_rep,
4092                     encoding=self.encoding,
4093                     errors=self.errors,
4094                 )
4095                 return Series(_set_tz(col_values[1], a.tz), name=column)
4096 
4097         raise KeyError(f"column [{column}] not found in the table")

4130 class AppendableTable(Table):
4131     """ support the new appendable table formats """
4132

4134 
4135     def write(
4136         self,
4137         obj,
4138         axes=None,
4139         append=False,
4140         complib=None,
4141         complevel=None,
4142         fletcher32=None,
4143         min_itemsize=None,
4144         chunksize=None,
4145         expectedrows=None,
4146         dropna=False,
4147         nan_rep=None,
4148         data_columns=None,
4149         track_times=True,
4150     ):
4151         if not append and self.is_exists:
4152             self._handle.remove_node(self.group, "table")
4153 
4154         # create the axes
4155         table = self._create_axes(
4156             axes=axes,
4157             obj=obj,
4158             validate=append,
4159             min_itemsize=min_itemsize,
4160             nan_rep=nan_rep,
4161             data_columns=data_columns,
4162         )
4163 
4164         for a in table.axes:
4165             a.validate_names()
4166 
4167         if not table.is_exists:
4168 
4169             # create the table
4170             options = table.create_description(
4171                 complib=complib,
4172                 complevel=complevel,
4173                 fletcher32=fletcher32,
4174                 expectedrows=expectedrows,
4175             )
4176 
4177             # set the table attributes
4178             table.set_attrs()
4179 
4180             options["track_times"] = track_times
4181 
4182             # create the table
4183             table._handle.create_table(table.group, **options)
4184 
4185         # update my info
4186         table.attrs.info = table.info
4187 
4188         # validate the axes and set the kinds
4189         for a in table.axes:
4190             a.validate_and_set(table, append)
4191 
4192         # add the rows
4193         table.write_data(chunksize, dropna=dropna)
4194 
4195     def write_data(self, chunksize: Optional[int], dropna: bool = False):
4196         """
4197         we form the data into a 2-d including indexes,values,mask write chunk-by-chunk
4198         """
4199         names = self.dtype.names
4200         nrows = self.nrows_expected
4201 
4202         # if dropna==True, then drop ALL nan rows
4203         masks = []
4204         if dropna:
4205 
4206             for a in self.values_axes:
4207 
4208                 # figure the mask: only do if we can successfully process this
4209                 # column, otherwise ignore the mask
4210                 mask = isna(a.data).all(axis=0)
4211                 if isinstance(mask, np.ndarray):
4212                     masks.append(mask.astype("u1", copy=False))
4213 
4214         # consolidate masks
4215         if len(masks):
4216             mask = masks[0]
4217             for m in masks[1:]:
4218                 mask = mask & m
4219             mask = mask.ravel()
4220         else:
4221             mask = None
4222 
4223         # broadcast the indexes if needed
4224         indexes = [a.cvalues for a in self.index_axes]
4225         nindexes = len(indexes)
4226         assert nindexes == 1, nindexes  # ensures we dont need to broadcast
4227 
4228         # transpose the values so first dimension is last
4229         # reshape the values if needed
4230         values = [a.take_data() for a in self.values_axes]
4231         values = [v.transpose(np.roll(np.arange(v.ndim), v.ndim - 1)) for v in values]
4232         bvalues = []
4233         for i, v in enumerate(values):
4234             new_shape = (nrows,) + self.dtype[names[nindexes + i]].shape
4235             bvalues.append(values[i].reshape(new_shape))
4236 
4237         # write the chunks
4238         if chunksize is None:
4239             chunksize = 100000
4240 
4241         rows = np.empty(min(chunksize, nrows), dtype=self.dtype)
4242         chunks = nrows // chunksize + 1
4243         for i in range(chunks):
4244             start_i = i * chunksize
4245             end_i = min((i + 1) * chunksize, nrows)
4246             if start_i >= end_i:
4247                 break
4248 
4249             self.write_data_chunk(
4250                 rows,
4251                 indexes=[a[start_i:end_i] for a in indexes],
4252                 mask=mask[start_i:end_i] if mask is not None else None,
4253                 values=[v[start_i:end_i] for v in bvalues],
4254             )
4255 
4256     def write_data_chunk(
4257         self,
4258         rows: np.ndarray,
4259         indexes: List[np.ndarray],
4260         mask: Optional[np.ndarray],
4261         values: List[np.ndarray],
4262     ):
4263         """
4264         Parameters
4265         ----------
4266         rows : an empty memory space where we are putting the chunk
4267         indexes : an array of the indexes
4268         mask : an array of the masks
4269         values : an array of the values
4270         """
4271         # 0 len
4272         for v in values:
4273             if not np.prod(v.shape):
4274                 return
4275 
4276         nrows = indexes[0].shape[0]
4277         if nrows != len(rows):
4278             rows = np.empty(nrows, dtype=self.dtype)
4279         names = self.dtype.names
4280         nindexes = len(indexes)
4281 
4282         # indexes
4283         for i, idx in enumerate(indexes):
4284             rows[names[i]] = idx
4285 
4286         # values
4287         for i, v in enumerate(values):
4288             rows[names[i + nindexes]] = v
4289 
4290         # mask
4291         if mask is not None:
4292             m = ~mask.ravel().astype(bool, copy=False)
4293             if not m.all():
4294                 rows = rows[m]
4295 
4296         if len(rows):
4297             self.table.append(rows)
4298             self.table.flush()
4299 
4300     def delete(
4301         self, where=None, start: Optional[int] = None, stop: Optional[int] = None,
4302     ):
4303 
4304         # delete all rows (and return the nrows)
4305         if where is None or not len(where):
4306             if start is None and stop is None:
4307                 nrows = self.nrows
4308                 self._handle.remove_node(self.group, recursive=True)
4309             else:
4310                 # pytables<3.0 would remove a single row with stop=None
4311                 if stop is None:
4312                     stop = self.nrows
4313                 nrows = self.table.remove_rows(start=start, stop=stop)
4314                 self.table.flush()
4315             return nrows
4316 
4317         # infer the data kind
4318         if not self.infer_axes():
4319             return None
4320 
4321         # create the selection
4322         table = self.table
4323         selection = Selection(self, where, start=start, stop=stop)
4324         values = selection.select_coords()
4325 
4326         # delete the rows in reverse order
4327         sorted_series = Series(values).sort_values()
4328         ln = len(sorted_series)
4329 
4330         if ln:
4331 
4332             # construct groups of consecutive rows
4333             diff = sorted_series.diff()
4334             groups = list(diff[diff > 1].index)
4335 
4336             # 1 group
4337             if not len(groups):
4338                 groups = [0]
4339 
4340             # final element
4341             if groups[-1] != ln:
4342                 groups.append(ln)
4343 
4344             # initial element
4345             if groups[0] != 0:
4346                 groups.insert(0, 0)
4347 
4348             # we must remove in reverse order!
4349             pg = groups.pop()
4350             for g in reversed(groups):
4351                 rows = sorted_series.take(range(g, pg))
4352                 table.remove_rows(
4353                     start=rows[rows.index[0]], stop=rows[rows.index[-1]] + 1
4354                 )
4355                 pg = g
4356 
4357             self.table.flush()
4358 
4359         # return the number of rows removed
4360         return ln

4363 class AppendableFrameTable(AppendableTable):
4364     """ support the new appendable table formats """
4365 
4366     pandas_kind = "frame_table"
4367     table_type = "appendable_frame"
4368     ndim = 2
4369     obj_type: Type[Union[DataFrame, Series]] = DataFrame
4370 
4371     @property
4372     def is_transposed(self) -> bool:
4373         return self.index_axes[0].axis == 1
4374 
4375     @classmethod
4376     def get_object(cls, obj, transposed: bool):
4377         """ these are written transposed """
4378         if transposed:
4379             obj = obj.T
4380         return obj
4381 
4382     def read(
4383         self,
4384         where=None,
4385         columns=None,
4386         start: Optional[int] = None,
4387         stop: Optional[int] = None,
4388     ):
4389 
4390         # validate the version
4391         self.validate_version(where)
4392 
4393         # infer the data kind
4394         if not self.infer_axes():
4395             return None
4396 
4397         result = self._read_axes(where=where, start=start, stop=stop)
4398 
4399         info = (
4400             self.info.get(self.non_index_axes[0][0], dict())
4401             if len(self.non_index_axes)
4402             else dict()
4403         )
4404 
4405         inds = [i for i, ax in enumerate(self.axes) if ax is self.index_axes[0]]
4406         assert len(inds) == 1
4407         ind = inds[0]
4408 
4409         index = result[ind][0]
4410 
4411         frames = []
4412         for i, a in enumerate(self.axes):
4413             if a not in self.values_axes:
4414                 continue
4415             index_vals, cvalues = result[i]
4416 
4417             # we could have a multi-index constructor here
4418             # ensure_index doesn't recognized our list-of-tuples here
4419             if info.get("type") == "MultiIndex":
4420                 cols = MultiIndex.from_tuples(index_vals)
4421             else:
4422                 cols = Index(index_vals)
4423 
4424             names = info.get("names")
4425             if names is not None:
4426                 cols.set_names(names, inplace=True)
4427 
4428             if self.is_transposed:
4429                 values = cvalues
4430                 index_ = cols
4431                 cols_ = Index(index, name=getattr(index, "name", None))
4432             else:
4433                 values = cvalues.T
4434                 index_ = Index(index, name=getattr(index, "name", None))
4435                 cols_ = cols
4436 
4437             # if we have a DataIndexableCol, its shape will only be 1 dim
4438             if values.ndim == 1 and isinstance(values, np.ndarray):
4439                 values = values.reshape((1, values.shape[0]))
4440 
4441             if isinstance(values, np.ndarray):
4442                 df = DataFrame(values.T, columns=cols_, index=index_)
4443             elif isinstance(values, Index):
4444                 df = DataFrame(values, columns=cols_, index=index_)
4445             else:
4446                 # Categorical
4447                 df = DataFrame([values], columns=cols_, index=index_)
4448             assert (df.dtypes == values.dtype).all(), (df.dtypes, values.dtype)
4449             frames.append(df)
4450 
4451         if len(frames) == 1:
4452             df = frames[0]
4453         else:
4454             df = concat(frames, axis=1)
4455 
4456         selection = Selection(self, where=where, start=start, stop=stop)
4457         # apply the selection filters & axis orderings
4458         df = self.process_axes(df, selection=selection, columns=columns)
4459 
4460         return df

4635 def _reindex_axis(obj: DataFrame, axis: int, labels: Index, other=None) -> DataFrame:
4636     ax = obj._get_axis(axis)
4637     labels = ensure_index(labels)
4638 
4639     # try not to reindex even if other is provided
4640     # if it equals our current index
4641     if other is not None:
4642         other = ensure_index(other)
4643     if (other is None or labels.equals(other)) and labels.equals(ax):
4644         return obj
4645 
4646     labels = ensure_index(labels.unique())
4647     if other is not None:
4648         labels = ensure_index(other.unique()).intersection(labels, sort=False)
4649     if not labels.equals(ax):
4650         slicer: List[Union[slice, Index]] = [slice(None, None)] * obj.ndim
4651         slicer[axis] = labels
4652         obj = obj.loc[tuple(slicer)]
4653     return obj

4659 def _get_tz(tz: tzinfo) -> Union[str, tzinfo]:
4660     """ for a tz-aware type, return an encoded zone """
4661     zone = timezones.get_timezone(tz)
4662     return zone

4664 
4665 def _set_tz(
4666     values: Union[np.ndarray, Index],
4667     tz: Optional[Union[str, tzinfo]],
4668     coerce: bool = False,
4669 ) -> Union[np.ndarray, DatetimeIndex]:
4670     """
4671     coerce the values to a DatetimeIndex if tz is set
4672     preserve the input shape if possible
4673 
4674     Parameters
4675     ----------
4676     values : ndarray or Index
4677     tz : str or tzinfo
4678     coerce : if we do not have a passed timezone, coerce to M8[ns] ndarray
4679     """
4680     if isinstance(values, DatetimeIndex):
4681         # If values is tzaware, the tz gets dropped in the values.ravel()
4682         #  call below (which returns an ndarray).  So we are only non-lossy
4683         #  if `tz` matches `values.tz`.
4684         assert values.tz is None or values.tz == tz
4685 
4686     if tz is not None:
4687         name = getattr(values, "name", None)
4688         values = values.ravel()
4689         tz = timezones.get_timezone(_ensure_decoded(tz))
4690         values = DatetimeIndex(values, name=name)
4691         values = values.tz_localize("UTC").tz_convert(tz)
4692     elif coerce:
4693         values = np.asarray(values, dtype="M8[ns]")
4694 
4695     return values
4696

4698 def _convert_index(name: str, index: Index, encoding: str, errors: str) -> IndexCol:
4699     assert isinstance(name, str)
4700 
4701     index_name = index.name
4702     converted, dtype_name = _get_data_and_dtype_name(index)
4703     kind = _dtype_to_kind(dtype_name)
4704     atom = DataIndexableCol._get_atom(converted)
4705 
4706     if isinstance(index, Int64Index):
4707         # Includes Int64Index, RangeIndex, DatetimeIndex, TimedeltaIndex, PeriodIndex,
4708         #  in which case "kind" is "integer", "integer", "datetime64",
4709         #  "timedelta64", and "integer", respectively.
4710         return IndexCol(
4711             name,
4712             values=converted,
4713             kind=kind,
4714             typ=atom,
4715             freq=getattr(index, "freq", None),
4716             tz=getattr(index, "tz", None),
4717             index_name=index_name,
4718         )
4719 
4720     if isinstance(index, MultiIndex):
4721         raise TypeError("MultiIndex not supported here!")
4722 
4723     inferred_type = lib.infer_dtype(index, skipna=False)
4724     # we won't get inferred_type of "datetime64" or "timedelta64" as these
4725     #  would go through the DatetimeIndex/TimedeltaIndex paths above
4726 
4727     values = np.asarray(index)
4728 
4729     if inferred_type == "date":
4730         converted = np.asarray([v.toordinal() for v in values], dtype=np.int32)
4731         return IndexCol(
4732             name, converted, "date", _tables().Time32Col(), index_name=index_name,
4733         )
4734     elif inferred_type == "string":
4735 
4736         converted = _convert_string_array(values, encoding, errors)
4737         itemsize = converted.dtype.itemsize
4738         return IndexCol(
4739             name,
4740             converted,
4741             "string",
4742             _tables().StringCol(itemsize),
4743             index_name=index_name,
4744         )
4745 
4746     elif inferred_type in ["integer", "floating"]:
4747         return IndexCol(
4748             name, values=converted, kind=kind, typ=atom, index_name=index_name,
4749         )
4750     else:
4751         assert isinstance(converted, np.ndarray) and converted.dtype == object
4752         assert kind == "object", kind
4753         atom = _tables().ObjectAtom()
4754         return IndexCol(name, converted, kind, atom, index_name=index_name,)
4755 
4756 
4757 def _unconvert_index(
4758     data, kind: str, encoding: str, errors: str
4759 ) -> Union[np.ndarray, Index]:
4760     index: Union[Index, np.ndarray]
4761 
4762     if kind == "datetime64":
4763         index = DatetimeIndex(data)
4764     elif kind == "timedelta64":
4765         index = TimedeltaIndex(data)
4766     elif kind == "date":
4767         try:
4768             index = np.asarray([date.fromordinal(v) for v in data], dtype=object)
4769         except (ValueError):
4770             index = np.asarray([date.fromtimestamp(v) for v in data], dtype=object)
4771     elif kind in ("integer", "float"):
4772         index = np.asarray(data)
4773     elif kind in ("string"):
4774         index = _unconvert_string_array(
4775             data, nan_rep=None, encoding=encoding, errors=errors
4776         )
4777     elif kind == "object":
4778         index = np.asarray(data[0])
4779     else:  # pragma: no cover
4780         raise ValueError(f"unrecognized index type {kind}")
4781     return index

4784 def _maybe_convert_for_string_atom(
4785     name: str, block, existing_col, min_itemsize, nan_rep, encoding, errors
4786 ):
4787 
4788     if not block.is_object:
4789         return block.values
4790 
4791     dtype_name = block.dtype.name
4792     inferred_type = lib.infer_dtype(block.values, skipna=False)
4793 
4794     if inferred_type == "date":
4795         raise TypeError("[date] is not implemented as a table column")
4796     elif inferred_type == "datetime":
4797         # after GH#8260
4798         # this only would be hit for a multi-timezone dtype which is an error
4799         raise TypeError(
4800             "too many timezones in this block, create separate data columns"
4801         )
4802 
4803     elif not (inferred_type == "string" or dtype_name == "object"):
4804         return block.values
4805 
4806     block = block.fillna(nan_rep, downcast=False)
4807     if isinstance(block, list):
4808         # Note: because block is always object dtype, fillna goes
4809         #  through a path such that the result is always a 1-element list
4810         block = block[0]
4811     data = block.values
4812 
4813     # see if we have a valid string type
4814     inferred_type = lib.infer_dtype(data, skipna=False)
4815     if inferred_type != "string":
4816 
4817         # we cannot serialize this data, so report an exception on a column
4818         # by column basis
4819         for i in range(len(block.shape[0])):
4820 
4821             col = block.iget(i)
4822             inferred_type = lib.infer_dtype(col, skipna=False)
4823             if inferred_type != "string":
4824                 iloc = block.mgr_locs.indexer[i]
4825                 raise TypeError(
4826                     f"Cannot serialize the column [{iloc}] because\n"
4827                     f"its data contents are [{inferred_type}] object dtype"
4828                 )
4829 
4830     # itemsize is the maximum length of a string (along any dimension)
4831     data_converted = _convert_string_array(data, encoding, errors).reshape(data.shape)
4832     assert data_converted.shape == block.shape, (data_converted.shape, block.shape)
4833     itemsize = data_converted.itemsize
4834 
4835     # specified min_itemsize?
4836     if isinstance(min_itemsize, dict):
4837         min_itemsize = int(min_itemsize.get(name) or min_itemsize.get("values") or 0)
4838     itemsize = max(min_itemsize or 0, itemsize)
4839 
4840     # check for column in the values conflicts
4841     if existing_col is not None:
4842         eci = existing_col.validate_col(itemsize)
4843         if eci > itemsize:
4844             itemsize = eci
4845 
4846     data_converted = data_converted.astype(f"|S{itemsize}", copy=False)
4847     return data_converted

4850 def _convert_string_array(data: np.ndarray, encoding: str, errors: str) -> np.ndarray:
4851     """
4852     Take a string-like that is object dtype and coerce to a fixed size string type.
4853 
4854     Parameters
4855     ----------
4856     data : np.ndarray[object]
4857     encoding : str
4858     errors : str
4859         Handler for encoding errors.
4860 
4861     Returns
4862     -------
4863     np.ndarray[fixed-length-string]
4864     """
4865     # encode if needed
4866     if len(data):
4867         data = (
4868             Series(data.ravel())
4869             .str.encode(encoding, errors)
4870             ._values.reshape(data.shape)
4871         )
4872 
4873     # create the sized dtype
4874     ensured = ensure_object(data.ravel())
4875     itemsize = max(1, libwriters.max_len_string_array(ensured))
4876 
4877     data = np.asarray(data, dtype=f"S{itemsize}")
4878     return data
4879 
4880 
4881 def _unconvert_string_array(
4882     data: np.ndarray, nan_rep, encoding: str, errors: str
4883 ) -> np.ndarray:
4884     """
4885     Inverse of _convert_string_array.
4886 
4887     Parameters
4888     ----------
4889     data : np.ndarray[fixed-length-string]
4890     nan_rep : the storage repr of NaN
4891     encoding : str
4892     errors : str
4893         Handler for encoding errors.
4894 
4895     Returns
4896     -------
4897     np.ndarray[object]
4898         Decoded data.
4899     """
4900     shape = data.shape
4901     data = np.asarray(data.ravel(), dtype=object)
4902 
4903     if len(data):
4904 
4905         itemsize = libwriters.max_len_string_array(ensure_object(data))
4906         dtype = f"U{itemsize}"
4907 
4908         if isinstance(data[0], bytes):
4909             data = Series(data).str.decode(encoding, errors=errors)._values
4910         else:
4911             data = data.astype(dtype, copy=False).astype(object, copy=False)
4912 
4913     if nan_rep is None:
4914         nan_rep = "nan"
4915 
4916     data = libwriters.string_array_replace_from_nan_rep(data, nan_rep)
4917     return data.reshape(shape)

4920 def _maybe_convert(values: np.ndarray, val_kind: str, encoding: str, errors: str):
4921     assert isinstance(val_kind, str), type(val_kind)
4922     if _need_convert(val_kind):
4923         conv = _get_converter(val_kind, encoding, errors)
4924         values = conv(values)
4925     return values

4928 def _get_converter(kind: str, encoding: str, errors: str):
4929     if kind == "datetime64":
4930         return lambda x: np.asarray(x, dtype="M8[ns]")
4931     elif kind == "string":
4932         return lambda x: _unconvert_string_array(
4933             x, nan_rep=None, encoding=encoding, errors=errors
4934         )
4935     else:  # pragma: no cover
4936         raise ValueError(f"invalid kind {kind}")
4937 
4938 
4939 def _need_convert(kind: str) -> bool:
4940     if kind in ("datetime64", "string"):
4941         return True
4942     return False

4945 def _maybe_adjust_name(name: str, version) -> str:
4946     """
4947     Prior to 0.10.1, we named values blocks like: values_block_0 an the
4948     name values_0, adjust the given name if necessary.
4949 
4950     Parameters
4951     ----------
4952     name : str
4953     version : Tuple[int, int, int]
4954 
4955     Returns
4956     -------
4957     str
4958     """
4959     try:
4960         if version[0] == 0 and version[1] <= 10 and version[2] == 0:
4961             m = re.search(r"values_block_(\d+)", name)
4962             if m:
4963                 grp = m.groups()[0]
4964                 name = f"values_{grp}"
4965     except IndexError:

4970 def _dtype_to_kind(dtype_str: str) -> str:
4971     """
4972     Find the "kind" string describing the given dtype name.
4973     """
4974     dtype_str = _ensure_decoded(dtype_str)
4975 
4976     if dtype_str.startswith("string") or dtype_str.startswith("bytes"):
4977         kind = "string"
4978     elif dtype_str.startswith("float"):
4979         kind = "float"
4980     elif dtype_str.startswith("complex"):
4981         kind = "complex"
4982     elif dtype_str.startswith("int") or dtype_str.startswith("uint"):
4983         kind = "integer"
4984     elif dtype_str.startswith("datetime64"):
4985         kind = "datetime64"
4986     elif dtype_str.startswith("timedelta"):
4987         kind = "timedelta64"
4988     elif dtype_str.startswith("bool"):
4989         kind = "bool"
4990     elif dtype_str.startswith("category"):
4991         kind = "category"
4992     elif dtype_str.startswith("period"):
4993         # We store the `freq` attr so we can restore from integers
4994         kind = "integer"
4995     elif dtype_str == "object":
4996         kind = "object"
4997     else:
4998         raise ValueError(f"cannot interpret dtype of [{dtype_str}]")
4999 
5000     return kind

5003 def _get_data_and_dtype_name(data: ArrayLike):
5004     """
5005     Convert the passed data into a storable form and a dtype string.
5006     """
5007     if isinstance(data, Categorical):
5008         data = data.codes
5009 
5010     # For datetime64tz we need to drop the TZ in tests TODO: why?
5011     dtype_name = data.dtype.name.split("[")[0]
5012 
5013     if data.dtype.kind in ["m", "M"]:
5014         data = np.asarray(data.view("i8"))
5015         # TODO: we used to reshape for the dt64tz case, but no longer
5016         #  doing that doesn't seem to break anything.  why?
5017 
5018     elif isinstance(data, PeriodIndex):
5019         data = data.asi8
5020 
5021     data = np.asarray(data)
5022     return data, dtype_name

5025 class Selection:
5026     """
5027     Carries out a selection operation on a tables.Table object.
5028 
5029     Parameters
5030     ----------
5031     table : a Table object
5032     where : list of Terms (or convertible to)
5033     start, stop: indices to start and/or stop selection
5034 
5035     """
5036 
5037     def __init__(
5038         self,
5039         table: Table,
5040         where=None,
5041         start: Optional[int] = None,
5042         stop: Optional[int] = None,
5043     ):
5044         self.table = table
5045         self.where = where
5046         self.start = start
5047         self.stop = stop
5048         self.condition = None
5049         self.filter = None
5050         self.terms = None
5051         self.coordinates = None
5052 
5053         if is_list_like(where):
5054 
5055             # see if we have a passed coordinate like
5056             try:
5057                 inferred = lib.infer_dtype(where, skipna=False)
5058                 if inferred == "integer" or inferred == "boolean":
5059                     where = np.asarray(where)
5060                     if where.dtype == np.bool_:
5061                         start, stop = self.start, self.stop
5062                         if start is None:
5063                             start = 0
5064                         if stop is None:
5065                             stop = self.table.nrows
5066                         self.coordinates = np.arange(start, stop)[where]
5067                     elif issubclass(where.dtype.type, np.integer):
5068                         if (self.start is not None and (where < self.start).any()) or (
5069                             self.stop is not None and (where >= self.stop).any()
5070                         ):
5071                             raise ValueError(
5072                                 "where must have index locations >= start and < stop"
5073                             )
5074                         self.coordinates = where
5075 
5076             except ValueError:
5077                 pass
5078 
5079         if self.coordinates is None:
5080 
5081             self.terms = self.generate(where)
5082 
5083             # create the numexpr & the filter
5084             if self.terms is not None:
5085                 self.condition, self.filter = self.terms.evaluate()
5086 
5087     def generate(self, where):
5088         """ where can be a : dict,list,tuple,string """
5089         if where is None:
5090             return None
5091 
5092         q = self.table.queryables()
5093         try:
5094             return PyTablesExpr(where, queryables=q, encoding=self.table.encoding)
5095         except NameError as err:
5096             # raise a nice message, suggesting that the user should use
5097             # data_columns
5098             qkeys = ",".join(q.keys())
5099             raise ValueError(
5100                 f"The passed where expression: {where}\n"
5101                 "            contains an invalid variable reference\n"
5102                 "            all of the variable references must be a "
5103                 "reference to\n"
5104                 "            an axis (e.g. 'index' or 'columns'), or a "
5105                 "data_column\n"
5106                 f"            The currently defined references are: {qkeys}\n"
5107             ) from err
5108 
5109     def select(self):
5110         """
5111         generate the selection
5112         """
5113         if self.condition is not None:
5114             return self.table.table.read_where(
5115                 self.condition.format(), start=self.start, stop=self.stop
5116             )
5117         elif self.coordinates is not None:
5118             return self.table.table.read_coordinates(self.coordinates)
5119         return self.table.table.read(start=self.start, stop=self.stop)
5120 
5121     def select_coords(self):
5122         """
5123         generate the selection
5124         """
5125         start, stop = self.start, self.stop
5126         nrows = self.table.nrows
5127         if start is None:
5128             start = 0
5129         elif start < 0:
5130             start += nrows
5131         if self.stop is None:
5132             stop = nrows
5133         elif stop < 0:
5134             stop += nrows
5135 
5136         if self.condition is not None:
5137             return self.table.table.get_where_list(
5138                 self.condition.format(), start=start, stop=stop, sort=True
5139             )
5140         elif self.coordinates is not None:
5141             return self.coordinates
5142 
5143         return np.arange(start, stop)
